You can implement the `IntoResponse` trait from the `axum` crate for the `sea_orm::DbErr` type to generate an appropriate HTTP response for your API. Here is an example:

```rust
use axum::{
    http::{StatusCode},
    response::{IntoResponse, Json},
};
use sea_orm::{DbErr, error::*, FromQueryResult};

impl IntoResponse for DbErr {
    type Body = Json<Self>;
    type BodyError = std::convert::Infallible;

    fn into_response(self) -> axum::http::Response<Self::Body> {
        Json(self).into_response().map(|mut res| {
            *res.status_mut() = match &self {
                DbErr::Exec(e) => match &**e {
                    DbErrKind::Query(_) => StatusCode::BAD_REQUEST,
                    _ => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
                },
                DbErr::Fetch(e) => match e {
                    FetchError::NotFound => StatusCode::NOT_FOUND,
                    FetchError::MultipleRowsReturned => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
                    _ => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
                },
                DbErr::Deserialization(_) => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
            };
            res
        })
    }
}
```

In this implementation, we first specify that the response body will be serialized as a `Json<DbErr>` value. Then, we map this JSON response using the `into_response()` method provided by `Json`, and modify the HTTP status code based on the type of `DbErr` error.

Finally, you can use this implementation in your `axum` service to automatically generate HTTP responses for `DbErr` errors returned from your API like this:

```rust
